[[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] '''Sir George Howard''' [[Order of the Bath|KB]], [[Privy Council of Great Britain|PC]] (17 June 1718 &ndash; 16 July 1796) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] military officer and politician. After commanding the [[Buffs (Royal East Kent Regiment)|3rd Regiment of Foot]] at the [[Battle of Fontenoy]] in May 1745 during the [[War of the Austrian Succession]] and after commanding that regiment again at the [[Battle of Falkirk Muir]] and the [[Battle of Culloden]] during the [[Jacobite risings|Jacobite Rebellion]], he returned to the continent and fought at the [[Battle of Lauffeld]]. He went on to command a brigade at the [[Battle of Warburg]] during the [[Seven Years' War]]. He subsequently became the [[Governor of Minorca]].

==Military career==
Born the son of [[Thomas Howard (British Army officer)|Lieutenant General Thomas Howard]] and his wife Mary Howard (née Moreton, daughter of [[William Moreton]], [[Bishop of Meath]]), Howard was educated at [[Westminster School]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]] and was [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] as a [[lieutenant]] in his father's regiment (later the [[South Wales Borderers|24th Regiment of Foot]]) in 1736.<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/13900?docPos=4|title=Sir George Howard|publisher=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> He was promoted to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in 1737 and transferred to the [[Buffs (Royal East Kent Regiment)|3rd Regiment of Foot]] in 1739.<ref name=heath179>Heathcote, p. 179</ref> Promoted to [[lieutenant colonel]] on 2 April 1744, he commanded the 3rd Regiment of Foot at the [[Battle of Fontenoy]] in May 1745 during the [[War of the Austrian Succession]].<ref name=heath179/>

Howard commanded the 3rd Regiment of Foot again, under the [[Prince William, Duke of Cumberland|Duke of Cumberland]], at the [[Battle of Falkirk Muir]] in January 1746 and the [[Battle of Culloden]] in April 1746 during the [[Jacobite risings|Jacobite Rebellion]] and was accused of treating the defeated highlanders unduely harshly.<ref name=heath179/> He then returned to the continent and fought at the [[Battle of Lauffeld]] in July 1747.<ref name=heath179/> He succeeded his father as colonel of the 3rd Regiment of Foot in August 1749.<ref name=heath180>Heathcote, p. 180</ref> He went on to take part in the [[Raid on Rochefort]] in September 1757 and, having been promoted to [[major-general]] on 24 January 1758,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=9759|supp=|startpage=1|date=21 January 1758|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> he commanded a brigade, under the [[John Manners, Marquess of Granby|Marquess of Granby]], at the [[Battle of Warburg]] in July 1760 during the [[Seven Years' War]].<ref name=heath180/> He was promoted to [[lieutenant-general]] on 14 March 1761.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=10086|supp=|startpage=2|date=10 March 1761|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref>

Howard became [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Lostwithiel (UK Parliament constituency)|Lostwithiel]] in 1761 and, having been appointed a [[Order of the Bath|Knight Companion of the Bath]] in early 1763, he became colonel of the [[7th Queen's Own Hussars|7th (The Queen's Own) Regiment of Dragoons]] in August 1763.<ref name=heath180/> He acquired [[Stoke Place]] in [[Buckinghamshire]] for use as a country home in 1764.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=42564|title=Parishes: Stoke Poges, A History of the County of Buckingham: Volume 3 (1925), |pages= 302–313|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>

Howard stood down from Parliament and became [[List of Governors of Minorca|Governor of Minorca]] in 1766.<ref name=heath180/> After retiring as Governor of Minorca, he became [[Governor]] of the [[Royal Hospital Chelsea]] in February 1768<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=98501#s2 |title=Survey of London, volume 11, edited by Walter H. Godfrey (editor)|year= 1927|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> and was elected as Member of Parliament for [[Stamford (UK Parliament constituency)|Stamford]] that same year.<ref name=heath180/>

Promoted to full [[general]] on 6 September 1777,<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=11802|supp=|startpage=2|date=2 September 1777|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> Howard became colonel of the [[1st King's Dragoon Guards|1st (The King's) Dragoon Guards]] in April 1779.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=11972|supp=|startpage=2|date=20 April 1779|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> He was promoted to [[Field marshal (United Kingdom)|field marshal]] on 18 October 1793<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13582|supp=|startpage=913|date=15 October 1793|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> and appointed to the honorary post of [[Lieutenant Governor of Jersey|Governor of Jersey]] in July 1795.<ref>{{LondonGazette|issue=13796|supp=|startpage=747|date=14 July 1795|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> He died at his London home in [[Grosvenor Square]] on 16 July 1796 and was buried at [[Great Bookham]] in [[Surrey]].<ref name=heath180/>

==Family==
In February 1747, Howard married Lady Lucy Wentworth (daughter of Sir William Wentworth of Northgate Head); they had one daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p3460.htm#i34598|title=Lady Lucy Wentworth|publisher=The Peerage.com|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> After the death of his first wife, Howard married Elizabeth Beckford; there were no children by the second marriage.<ref name=odnb/>
